07695nam a22015495i 9780691184944DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20192018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911849447 a10.1515/97806911849442doi  a(DE-B1597)501773  a(OCoLC)1057893475  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBR307 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a274.062231 aShagan, Ethan H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Birth of Modern Belief :bFaith and Judgment from the Middle Ages to the Enlightenment /cEthan H. Shagan. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b4 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Medieval Varieties of Believing -- tChapter 2. The Reformation of Belief -- tChapter 3. The Invention of the Unbeliever -- tChapter 4. The Unbearable Weight of Believing -- tChapter 5. The Birth Pangs of Modern Belief -- tChapter 6. Enlightened Belief -- tChapter 7. Belief in the Human -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn illuminating history of how religious belief lost its uncontested status in the WestThis landmark book traces the history of belief in the Christian West from the Middle Ages to the Enlightenment, revealing for the first time how a distinctively modern category of belief came into being. Ethan Shagan focuses not on what people believed, which is the normal concern of Reformation history, but on the more fundamental question of what people took belief to be.Shagan shows how religious belief enjoyed a special prestige in medieval Europe, one that set it apart from judgment, opinion, and the evidence of the senses. But with the outbreak of the Protestant Reformation, the question of just what kind of knowledge religious belief was-and how it related to more mundane ways of knowing-was forced into the open. As the warring churches fought over the answer, each claimed belief as their exclusive possession, insisting that their rivals were unbelievers. Shagan challenges the common notion that modern belief was a gift of the Reformation, showing how it was as much a reaction against Luther and Calvin as it was against the Council of Trent. He describes how dissidents on both sides came to regard religious belief as something that needed to be justified by individual judgment, evidence, and argument.Brilliantly illuminating, The Birth of Modern Belief demonstrates how belief came to occupy such an ambivalent place in the modern world, becoming the essential category by which we express our judgments about science, society, and the sacred, but at the expense of the unique status religion once enjoyed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aBelief and doubtxHistory. 0aFaithxHistory of doctrines. 0aReformation. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aAnabaptists.  aCalvin.  aCatholics.  aChristian West.  aChristian belief.  aChristian society.  aChurch.  aCouncil of Trent.  aCounter-Reformation.  aDescartes.  aEnlightenment.  aEurope.  aFrancesco Spiera.  aGod.  aLuther.  aProtestant Reformation.  aProtestants.  aReformation.  aSamuel Taylor Coleridge.  aatheism.  abelief.  abirth pangs.  aclassical philosophy.  aconfessional credulity.  adeity.  adoctrines.  adogma.  aeighteenth century.  aepistemology.  aevil.  aexistence.  afaith.  ahuman beings.  ahuman creations.  ahuman judgment.  ainfidels.  ainfinite creator.  aknowledge.  amedieval Christians.  amedieval credulity.  amodern belief.  amodern cr